\begin{abstract}
  %% Since independence India has undergone substantial land cover change as a result of population growth and economic development. Historical, spatially-explicit land cover data showing the change that has taken place is necessary to quantify the impact of land cover change at global and regional scales, improve predictions about the quantity and location of future change and support planning decisions, as well as forming the basis of maps of land use intensity. Here, the Change in Land Use and its Effects regional land use change model is used to develop historical land cover maps for the entire Indian subcontinent between 1956 and 2010 at 5 arcminute resolution. The algorithm combines a state of the art contemporary land cover product, GlobeLand30, with district-level inventory data. In contrast to existing datasets, which are based on the assumption that the historical distribution of land cover is the same as the present distribution, the methodology accounts for socio-economic and biophysical conditions. \\

In recent decades India has undergone substantial land cover change as a result of population growth and economic development. Historical land use/land cover maps are necessary to quantify the impact of change at global and regional scales, improve predictions about the quantity and location of future change and support planning decisions, as well as provide the basis for maps of land use intensity and management. Here, a regional land use change model, driven by district-level land use/land cover inventory data, is used to generate a time series of high-resolution land use/land cover maps for the Indian subcontinent between 1956--2010. The allocation procedure is based on a statistical analysis of the relationship between contemporary land use/land cover distribution and various spatially explicit socioeconomic and biophysical covariates. The derived regression equations are used to identify the suitability of individual pixels to the respective land use/land cover types. Change in a particular land use/land cover type is allocated preferentially to pixels with a relatively high suitability. The resulting maps were evaluated against alternative land use/land cover reconstructions as well as a state-of-the-art dataset providing land use/land cover maps derived from classified Landsat images. \\ 

