\section*{Methods}

\subsection*{The HILDA land change model}
The HIstoric Land Dynamics Assessment (HILDA) land change model \cite{fuchs_high-resolution_2013,fuchs_gross_2015} simulates land use/land cover change over a spatial grid in which individual cells belong to a single land use/land cover type. HILDA was originally developed for reconstructing historical land use/land cover change in Europe \cite{fuchs_high-resolution_2013}. The model is relatively simple compared to more sophisticated approaches such as the CLUE family of models \cite[e.g.]{verburg_spatial_2002,verburg_combining_2009}. However, it is computationally efficient and guaranteed to produce a solution which satisfies the regional land change requirement; as such it is well suited to modelling land change over large study regions. The allocation procedure is based on statistical analysis of the quantitative relationship between the contemporary distribution of land use/land cover and various socioeconomic and biophysical predictor variables. The resulting regression models are used to estimate the probability of grid cells belonging to the respective land use/land cover type given the underlying biophysical and socioeconomic conditions. At each time point in the simulation period the model spatially allocates a given quantity of change amongst the various land use/land cover types. Allocation proceeds in a hierarchical way according to the relative socioeconomic value of the various land use/land cover types under consideration. Land uses with increasing area at the regional level are only allowed to expand to areas currently occupied by land uses with lower socioeconomic value. In this case, \textit{n} cells with the highest probability of belonging to the land use, but which do not currently belong to to it, are selected to change. In the case of land uses with decreasing area, \textit{n} cells currently belonging to the land use are nominated for conversion to an alternative land use. We modified HILDA to include stochastic transitions, such that land use transitions are only made if the relevant probability value exceeds a random number \textit{x} drawn from a uniform distribution, such that $0 \leq x \leq 1$.

