\subsubsection*{Biophysical and socio-economic predictor variables}
The HILDA model is based on statistical relationships between land use/land cover and spatially-explicit biophysical and socio-economic predictor variables. Nine covariables were used in total (Table XYZ). Data on topography (elevation, slope, aspect), which is known as an important determinant of land use/land cover \cite{}, was derived from the HydroSHEDS database \cite{}, which itself is derived from the NASA Shuttle Radar Topographic Mission digital elevation model \cite{}. Bioclimatic variables assumed to influence the spatial configuration of the landscape were obtained from the BIOCLIM dataset \cite{fick_worldclim_2017}. \\

A map of population density for 2010 at 100m resolution was obtained from the WorldPop database \cite{gaughan_high_2013}, which represents the state-of-the-art in global population mapping \cite{}. The map was produced by spatially downscaling subnational population counts on the basis of land cover and urban extent \cite{linard_population_2012}. Accessibility, which strongly influences the location of cropland \cite{}, was primarily represented by a map showing the estimated travel time to the nearest city with a population of 50,000 or more for the year 2000. Additionally, distance to roads was estimated using a map of major roads from the Global Roads Open Access Dataset (version 1) \cite{}. \\

