The raw district-level inventory data is associated with a large amount of noise which had to be manually removed before supplying it to the CLUE model. To ensure decisions made during data quality control are open, reproducible and amendable the R scripts used to process the data are included alongside the land use/land cover change dataset (Data Citation 1). In addition, while the GlobeLand30 dataset represents the state of the art in global land use/land cover mapping, it is nevertheless associated with uncertainty in both the quantity and spatial distribution of land use/land cover. One way to account for this uncertainty would be to repeat the analysis using alternative remote sensing datasets. Detailed instructions for using alternative input datasets are provided with the source code (Data Citation 1). \\

The CLUE model is strongly influenced by the statistical analysis of the spatial distribution of contemporary land use/land cover. The random forest models employed in the present study use several publicly available datasets including soil quality, topography, population distribution and NDVI in addition to the GlobeLand30 dataset from which the dependent variable of each model is derived. Recognising that other members of the community may have access to alternative, or additional, datasets outside the public domain, the source code includes clear instructions about incorporating additional data into the statistical analysis. \\

Defining the extent of land use/land cover is a necessary first step towards developing datasets of land use intensity. The lack of such datasets is one of the main reasons for the large uncertainty about the influence of the biosphere on global and regional change \cite{houghton2012}. In India, while the area devoted to agriculture has increased by approximately 5\% during the study period, the fraction of cropland that is irrigated at least once during the agricultural year has increased by around 60\% according to the raw inventory data. There has also been a dramatic rise in the amount of fertiliser applied to agricultural land. The district-level inventory data used in the current study (Data Citation 2) includes irrigated area by crop and source as well information about fertiliser application and agricultural mechanisation. Future work should develop algorithms to combine estimates of historical cropland extent with information about land use intensity. \\

